 meaning ‘purple’) or more commonly a pet form of Middle English and Old French <i>Basile</i> or <i>Basily</i>, used of men and women alike. Compare   Basley   and   Basil  .","English: in some instances, from Middle English <i>bærs</i>, <i>bas</i> ‘freshwater perch, bass or any of various related or similar fish, such as the sea bass’, hence a nickname for a person supposedly resembling this fish, or a metonymic occupational name for a fish seller or fisherman."],"variants":[{"name":"Basley","meanings":["English (Northamptonshire): from the Middle English personal name <i>Basile</i> or <i>Basily</i>, used for men and women alike. It is a borrowing of Old French <i>Basil(e)</i>, from Latin <i>Basilius</i> (see   Basil  ) and its feminine form <i>Basilia</i>. For a pet form of the name see   Bass  ."]},{"name":"Baskin","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of Irish <b>Ó Baiscinn</b>, from the personal name <i>Bascaoin</i> meaning ‘fair of hand’. The surname arose from a historical population group called <i>Corca Bhaiscinn</i> ‘seed of <i>Bascaoin</i>’ in west County Clare, and is independent of the Norman name (see 3 below).","English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English personal name <i>Baskin</i>, a borrowing of Flemish or Picard <i>Basequin</i>, a pet form of <i>Base</i> (ancient Germanic <i>Baso</i>, perhaps meaning ‘purple’) + the diminutive suffix <i>-kin</i>. It could also have been used as a pet form of Old French <i>Basile</i>. See   Bass  .","Jewish (from Belarus and Ukraine): metronymic, formed with the Slavic possessive suffix <i>-in</i>, from the Yiddish female personal name <i>Baske</i>, a pet form of the Biblical name <i>Bath Seba</i> under the influence of Polish <i>Basia</i>, a pet form of <i>Barbara</i>."]},{"name":"Baskett","meanings":["English:","from Middle English <i>basket</i> ‘basket’, hence a metonymic occupational name for a basket maker, or perhaps for someone who carried a basket or pannier as part of his work, for example, carrying baskets of stone to a lime kiln. In some cases it appears to have been a topographic or habitational name referring to a house distinguished by the sign of a basket (probably owned by a basket maker).","variant of <b>Bascott</b>, a habitational name from Bascote in Warwickshire, probably so named with an unattested Old English personal name <i>Basuca</i> + <i>cot</i> ‘cottage’."]},{"name":"Bayes","meanings":["English: variant of   Bass   1-3."]},{"name":"Base","meanings":["English (Norfolk): variant of   Bass  .","German (<b>Bäse</b>): variant of <b>Bese</b> (see   Beese  ). Compare   Baese  ."]}]},{"name":"Woocroft","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Rycroft  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Rycroft","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): variant of   Roycroft  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Woocroft Bass was born in 1430, in Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son with Elizabeth Annesly. He died in 1490, in his hometown, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1430–1490":"1430–1490","1435–1500":"1435–1500","1455–1482":"1455–1482","1435":"1435","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1430":"1430","after 1482":"pärast 1482","1482":"1482","1490":"1490","Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hertfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom":"Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Scroby, Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1430–1490":"1430–1490","1435–1500":"1435–1500","1455–1482":"1455–1482","1435":"1435","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1430":"1430","after 1482":"1482 jälkeen","1482":"1482","1490":"1490","Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hertfordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom":"Warwickshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Scroby, Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1430–1490":"14